    },
    "Content": {
      "contentTitle": "Get Started",
      "contentBody": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": {
            "id": "1",
            "textLabel": "Welcome! Java is one of the world’s most popular programming languages. It is used to build desktop apps, backend servers, Android apps, scientific systems, games, and enterprise software."
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "image",
          "value": {
            "id": "1-img",
            "src": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/3/30/Java_programming_language_logo.svg",
            "textLabel": "Java Logo",
            "style": {
              "margin": "0 auto",
              "width": "200px",
              "display": "block"
            }
          }
        },

        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": {
            "id": "1-1",
            "textLabel": "Java is an object-oriented, high-level, platform-independent language. It uses the JVM (Java Virtual Machine) to run programs, making Java code portable across Windows, Mac, Linux, and other systems."
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": {
            "id": "1-1b",
            "textLabel": "Java is widely used because:\n• It is easy to read and write\n• Highly secure and reliable\n• Runs everywhere (Write Once, Run Anywhere)\n• Huge libraries and frameworks\n• Backed by decades of community support"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "value": {
            "id": "1-1c",
            "language": "java",
            "code": "public class Hello {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        System.out.println(\"Welcome to Java!\");\n    }\n}"
          }
        },

        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": {
            "id": "1-2",
            "textLabel": "To install Java, download the latest JDK from Oracle or OpenJDK. After installation, verify it using the command:"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "value": {
            "id": "1-2b",
            "language": "bash",
            "code": "java -version"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  },
  "2": {
    "Main Line": {
      "label": "Syntax",
      "color": "#FFFFFF",
      "links": [
        { "text": "2.1 Java Syntax", "href": "#2-1" },
        { "text": "2.2 Java I/O", "href": "#2-2" }
      ],
      "examId" : [1]
    },
    "Content": {
      "contentTitle": "Java Syntax Overview",
      "contentBody": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": {
            "id": "2",
            "textLabel": "Java syntax defines rules on how Java code must be written. Java is case-sensitive, requires class definitions, and enforces strict structure."
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "codeBlock",
          "value": {
            "id": "2-1",
            "code": "public class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        System.out.println(\"Hello Java!\");\n    }\n}",
            "output": "Hello Java!"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": {
            "id": "2-1b",
            "textLabel": "Key Java syntax elements:\n• Classes hold code\n• Methods perform actions\n• Statements end with semicolons\n• Blocks use curly braces"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": {
            "id": "2-2",
            "textLabel": "Java I/O (Input / Output) allows you to interact with users. The Scanner class is commonly used for input."
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "codeBlock",
          "value": {
            "id": "2-2b",
            "code": "import java.util.Scanner;\n\nScanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);\nSystem.out.print(\"Enter your name: \");\nString name = sc.nextLine();\nSystem.out.println(\"Hello \" + name);",
            "output": "Enter your name: John\nHello John"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  },
  "3": {
    "Main Line": {
      "label": "Data Types",
      "color": "#FFFFFF",
      "links": [
        { "text": "3.1 Java Data Types", "href": "#3-1" },
        { "text": "3.2 Java Type Casting", "href": "#3-2" }
      ],
      "examId" : [1]
    },
    "Content": {
      "contentTitle": "Java Data Types",
      "contentBody": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": {
            "id": "3",
            "textLabel": "Java supports two major categories of data types: primitive types and reference types."
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": {
            "id": "3-1",
            "textLabel": "Primitive types:\nbyte, short, int, long, float, double, boolean, char"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "value": {
            "id": "3-1b",
            "code": "int age = 21;\ndouble price = 19.99;\nboolean isJavaFun = true;\nchar grade = 'A';"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": {
            "id": "3-2",
            "textLabel": "Type casting converts a value from one type to another.\n• Widening (automatic)\n• Narrowing (manual)"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "value": {
            "id": "3-2b",
            "code": "int num = 10;\ndouble converted = num; // widening\n\ndouble x = 5.7;\nint y = (int)x; // narrowing"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  },
  "4": {
    "Main Line": {
      "label": "Operator",
      "color": "#FFFFFF",
      "links": [
        { "text": "4.1 Java Operator", "href": "#4-1" },
        { "text": "4.2 Arithmetic", "href": "#4-2" },
        { "text": "4.3 Comparison", "href": "#4-3" },
        { "text": "4.4 Logical", "href": "#4-4" }
      ],
      "examId" : [2]
    },
    "Content": {
      "contentTitle": "Java Operators",
      "contentBody": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": {
            "id": "4-1",
            "textLabel": "Operators allow you to perform actions on variables. They include arithmetic, logical, comparison, bitwise, and more."
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "codeBlock",
          "value": {
            "id": "4-2",
            "code": "int a = 10, b = 5;\nSystem.out.println(a + b);\nSystem.out.println(a - b);\nSystem.out.println(a * b);\nSystem.out.println(a / b);",
            "output": "15\n5\n50\n2"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "codeBlock",
          "value": {
            "id": "4-3",
            "code": "int x = 10, y = 20;\nSystem.out.println(x > y);\nSystem.out.println(x == 10);",
            "output": "false\ntrue"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "codeBlock",
          "value": {
            "id": "4-4",
            "code": "boolean a = true;\nboolean b = false;\nSystem.out.println(a && b);\nSystem.out.println(a || b);",
            "output": "false\ntrue"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  },
  "5": {
    "Main Line": {
      "label": "Java If - Else",
      "color": "#FFFFFF",
      "links": [
        { "text": "5.1 If Statement", "href": "#5-1" },
        { "text": "5.2 Else Statement", "href": "#5-2" },
        { "text": "5.3 Else If Statement", "href": "#5-3" },
        { "text": "5.4 Nested If", "href": "#5-4" }
      ],
      "examId" : [2]
    },
    "Content": {
      "contentTitle": "Java If/Else",
      "contentBody": [
        {
          "type": "codeBlock",
          "value": {
            "id": "5-1",
            "code": "int age = 18;\nif (age >= 18) {\n    System.out.println(\"You are an adult.\");\n}",
            "output": "You are an adult."
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "codeBlock",
          "value": {
            "id": "5-2",
            "code": "int score = 40;\nif (score >= 50) {\n    System.out.println(\"Pass\");\n} else {\n    System.out.println(\"Fail\");\n}",
            "output": "Fail"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "codeBlock",
          "value": {
            "id": "5-3",
            "code": "int temp = 30;\nif (temp > 35) {\n    System.out.println(\"Hot\");\n} else if (temp > 20) {\n    System.out.println(\"Warm\");\n} else {\n    System.out.println(\"Cold\");\n}",
            "output": "Warm"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "codeBlock",
          "value": {
            "id": "5-4",
            "code": "int a = 10, b = 5;\nif (a > 0) {\n    if (b > 0) {\n        System.out.println(\"Both positive\");\n    }\n}",
            "output": "Both positive"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  },
  "6": {
    "Main Line": {
      "label": "Loops",
      "color": "#FFFFFF",
      "links": [
        { "text": "6.1 While Loop", "href": "#6-1" },
        { "text": "6.2 For Loop", "href": "#6-2" },
        { "text": "6.3 For Each Loop", "href": "#6-3" },
        { "text": "6.4 Nested Loop", "href": "#6-4" }
      ],
      "examId" : [2]
    },
    "Content": {
      "contentTitle": "Loops",
      "contentBody": [
        {
          "type": "codeBlock",
          "value": {
            "id": "6-1",
            "code": "int i = 1;\nwhile (i <= 5) {\n    System.out.println(i);\n    i++;\n}",
            "output": "1\n2\n3\n4\n5"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "codeBlock",
          "value": {
            "id": "6-2",
            "code": "for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {\n    System.out.println(i);\n}",
            "output": "1\n2\n3\n4\n5"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "codeBlock",
          "value": {
            "id": "6-3",
            "code": "int[] nums = {10, 20, 30};\nfor (int n : nums) {\n    System.out.println(n);\n}",
            "output": "10\n20\n30"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "codeBlock",
          "value": {
            "id": "6-4",
            "code": "for (int i = 1; i <= 3; i++) {\n    for (int j = 1; j <= 3; j++) {\n        System.out.println(i + \" \" + j);\n    }\n}",
            "output": "1 1\n1 2\n1 3\n2 1\n2 2\n2 3\n3 1\n3 2\n3 3"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  },
